SIMPLE: symbolize
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Symbolize
<hw>Sym"bol*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Symbolized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Symbolizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>symboliser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To have a resemblance of
qualities or properties; to correspond; to harmonize.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pleasing of color <qex>symbolizeth</qex> with the pleasing of
any single tone to the ear; but the pleasing of order doth
<qex>symbolize</qex> with harmony.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They both <qex>symbolize</qex> in this, that they love to look
upon themselves through multiplying glasses.</q>
<rj><qau>Howell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To hold the same faith; to agree.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The believers in pretended miracles have always previously
<qex>symbolized</qex> with the performers of them.</q> <rj><qau>G. S.
Faber.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To use symbols; to represent ideas
symbolically.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Symbolize</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Symbolize
<hw>Sym"bol*ize</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make to agree
in properties or qualities.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make representative of something; to regard or
treat as symbolic.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Some <xex>symbolize</xex> the same from
the mystery of its colors.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To represent by a symbol or symbols.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Symbolizer</ent>⟦br⟧
